The majority of CPPs utilised in the DMD field (Table 1, Table 2
) may be covalently linked to PMO [31], [85]. However, another class of non-covalent peptides from the Transportan family has been engineered to deliver anionic SSOs such as 2′OMePS, as detailed in Section 6
[86]. A number of modifications of stearylated TP10 [87] gave rise to CPPs capable of inducing high splice correction in vitro in murine H2k mdx myotubes (PepFect6; [51] and PepFect14; [88]) (Table 1). It should be noted that the in vivo efficacies of these CPPs have yet to be assessed.
